&lt;/span>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>This was my second game released on Google Play. It featured a few levels where the goal was to land a rocket by controlling its left and right thrusters.&lt;/p></description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="/published-games/1727633156684-land-it/featured.png"/></item><item><title>Procedural Planet Generator</title><link>/personal-projects/1727103437739-planet-generator/</link><pubDate>Sat, 21 Jun 2014 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>/personal-projects/1727103437739-planet-generator/</guid><description>&lt;h2 class="relative group">Planet Generator: A Lost but Memorable Early Project
&lt;div id="planet-generator-a-lost-but-memorable-early-project" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#planet-generator-a-lost-but-memorable-early-project" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>This is definitely one of my oldest projects, which unfortunately got lost with only a few screenshots remaining. However, it&amp;rsquo;s significant enough that I want to write about it. It was a planet generator I was developing for a space exploration survival game. Back then, I didn&amp;rsquo;t realize how massive a challenge creating such a game would be, but I learned a lot from the experience.
The generator was able to create a height map, generate sphere geometry, subdivide and refine it, and place points based on the height map. It could also recursively split the sphere into smaller chunks.&lt;/p></description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="/personal-projects/1727103437739-planet-generator/featured.png"/></item></channel></rss>